 statue delivered to Pembroke 'hometown' |date= 8 June 2017 |accessdate=30 January 2020|work= BBC News}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art footer}}\n\n==Pembroke Dock==\n{{Public art header|show_architect=no|show_material=yes|show_dimensions=yes|show_owner=no|show_wikidata=yes}}\n{{Public art row\n| image = Pembroke Dock War Memorial - geograph.org.uk - 4397627.jpg\n| commonscat = \n| subject = War memorial\n| location = Churchyard of St John the Evangelist, [[Pembroke Dock]]\n| date = 1921\n| show_artist= \n| artist = [[John Coates Carter]]\n| type = Calvery on pedestal & stepped plinth\n| material = Red sandstone calvary, stone pedestal & limestone plinth\n| dimensions =\n| designation = Grade II\n| coordinates = \n| show_wikidata= yes\n| wikidata = Q29492184\n| notes = <ref>{{cadw |num= 14346 |desc= War memorial |accessdate= 29 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=|url= https://www.iwm.org.uk/memorials/item/memorial/6822 |title=War Memorials Register, Pembroke Dock |date= |accessdate=30 January 2020|work=Imperial War Museum}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art footer}}\n\n==St Davids==\n{{Public art header|show_architect=no|show_material=yes|show_dimensions=yes|show_owner=no|show_wikidata=yes}}\n{{Public art row\n| image = City Cross, St David&#039;s (8356).jpg\n| commonscat = City Cross, St David's\n| subject = The City Cross \n| location = [[St Davids]]\n| date = Shaft, c.14th Century; Head, 1873\n| show_artist= \n| artist = \n| type = Octagonial Celtic cross \n| material = Stone\n| dimensions = \n| designation = Grade II*\n| coordinates = \n| show_wikidata= yes\n| wikidata = Q17743347\n| notes = <ref>{{cadw |num= 12575 |desc= The City Cross |accessdate= 30 January 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art footer}}\n\n==Tenby==\n{{Public art header|show_architect=no|show_material=yes|show_dimensions=yes|show_owner=no|show_wikidata=yes}}\n{{Public art row\n| image = Welsh Memorial to Prince Albert 20190925 095449 (48792295156).jpg \n| commonscat = Statue of Albert, Prince Consort (Tenby) \n| subject = [[Albert, Prince Consort |Prince Albert]]\n| location = [[Tenby]]\n| date = 1864-5\n| show_artist= yes\n| artist = [[John Evan Thomas]]\n| type = Statue\n| material = Marble statue on stone pedestal\n| dimensions = Statue 2.7m tall\n| designation =   \n| coordinates =\n| show_wikidata= yes\n| wikidata = \n| notes = <ref name=\"Albert\">{{cite web |author=|url= https://coflein.gov.uk/en/site/32951/details/prince-consort-memorial-prince-albert-memorial-tenby|title= Prince Consort Memorial; Prince Albert Memorial, Tenby |date=|accessdate=29 January 2020|work=Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Wales}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image = Dyster Memorial Drinking Fountain in Tenby (6719).jpg\n| commonscat =  \n| subject = Dyster Memorial Drinking Fountain \n| location = Tenby\n| date = 1867\n| show_artist= yes\n| artist = F R Kempson\n| type = Octagonal column with fountains & gas lamp\n| material = Stone\n| dimensions = \n| designation = Grade II \n| coordinates =\n| show_wikidata= yes\n| wikidata = \n| notes = Memorial to Lt Col Thomas Josiah Wedgewood, 1798-1860, presented by Tenby mayor, Dr  F D Dyster.<ref>{{cadw |num= 6293 |desc=Memorial fountain, Tenby |accessdate= 29 January 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image = Tenby War Memorial \u2013 20190925 143053 (48792836463).jpg \n| commonscat = Tenby War Memorial\n| subject = War memorial\n| location = Tenby\n| date = 1921\n| show_artist= \n| artist = J Howard Morgan and G H Beynon\n| type = Pillar\n| material = Stone pillar with marble panels\n| dimensions = 3.5m high\n| designation = \n| coordinates = \n| show_wikidata= yes\n| wikidata =\n| notes =  <ref>{{cite web |author=|url= https://www.iwm.org.uk/memorials/item/memorial/2810 |title=War Memorials Register, Tenby |date= |accessdate=29 January 2020|work=Imperial War Museum}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=|url=https://historypoints.org/index.php?page=tenby-war-memorial |title=Tenby war memorial|date=|accessdate=6 February 2020|work=historypoints.org}}</ref><ref name=\"Pevsner\"/>\n}}\n{{Public art footer}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Pembrokeshire}}\n{{UK public art}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Public art in Pembrokeshire}}\n[[Category:Lists of public art in Wales|Pembrokeshire]]\n", "name_user": "Ham II", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_public_art_in_Pembrokeshire"}
{"title_page": "Hugh Henry Breckenridge", "text_new": "{{Short description|American painter}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name           = Hugh Henry Breckenridge\n| image          = Breckenridge Selfportrait 1913.jpg\n| imagesize      =\n| caption        = Self-portrait 1913\n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1870|10|6|mf=y}}\n| birth_place    = Leesburg, Virginia\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1937|11|4|1870|10|6|mf=y}} \n| death_place   = Philadelphia, Pennsylvania\n| nationality   = American\n| education     = Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts\n| field         = [[Painting]], [[Educator]]\n| training      =\n| movement      = \n| works         = \n| patrons       =\n| awards        = \n| spouse        = \n}}\n\n'''Hugh Henry Breckenridge''' (1870-1937), was an American painter and art instructor who championed the artistic movements from impressionism to modernism. Breckenridge taught for more than forty years at the [[Pennsylvania Academy of Fine Arts]], becoming the school's Dean of Instruction in 1934. He also taught from 1920 to 1937 at his own Breckenridge School of Art in [[Gloucester, Massachusetts]]. \n  \n==Biography==\nBreckenridge was born on October 6, 1870 in Leesburg, Virginia. He attended the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts where he met first met [[William Edmondson]].<ref name=\"SullivanGoss\">{{cite web|last1=MacDonald|first1=Aubrey E.|title=Hugh Breckenridge (1870-1937)|url=http://www.sullivangoss.com/hugh_Breckenridge/|website=Sullivan Goss|accessdate=21 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822070636/http://www.sullivangoss.com/hugh_Breckenridge/|archive-date=22 August 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1892, he traveled to Paris where he studied under [[Adolphe William Bouguereau]].<ref name=\"askART\">{{cite web|title=Hugh Breckenridge  (1870 - 1937)|url=http://www.askart.com/artist/Hugh_Henry_Breckenridge/89871/Hugh_Henry_Breckenridge.aspx|website=askART|accessdate=21 April 2018}}</ref> He travelled through Europe with his colleague [[Walter Elmer Schofield|Walter E. Schofield]].<ref name=\"askART\"/>\n\nIn 1894 when he returned to Philadelphia he began his career at the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts (PAFA), where he would teach for more than forty years.<ref name=\"askART\"/><ref name=\"Tran\">{{cite web|last1=Tran|first1=Hoang|title=Hugh Breckenridge papers: Finding Aid|url=https://www.pafa.org/sites/default/files/media-assets/MS.036_HughBreckenridge.pdf|website=Dorothy and Kenneth Woodcock Archives|publisher=The Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nBreckenridge opened his own school in Gloucester, Massachusetts, the Breckenridge School of Art, where he taught summer classes every year from 1920 to 1937.<ref>{{cite book | title=Paintings & Sculpture at the National Academy of Design: 1826-1925 | volume=1 | first=David B. | last=Dearinger | page=64}}</ref>\n\nBreckenridge exhibited widely from 1896 until his death, starting at the [[Art Club of Philadelphia]] and, towards the end of his life, in 1934, at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art|Whitney Museum]].<ref name=\"SullivanGoss\"/> His work was included in the 1926 [[Sesquicentennial Exposition|Philadelphia Sesqui-Centennial Exhibition]].<ref name=\"SullivanGoss\"/>\n\nBreckenridge was a member of the [[Philadelphia Art Alliance]], [[Philadelphia Sketch Club]], and the Arts Club of Philadelphia.<ref name=\"SullivanGoss\"/>\n\nHe died on November 4, 1937 in Philadelphia, while he was still on the faculty of the PAFA.<ref name=\"Tran\"/><ref name=\"SullivanGoss\"/>\n<gallery widths=\"165px\" heights=\"165px\">\nFile:Hugh Henry Breckenridge, White Phlox, 1906, oil on canvas, Terra Foundation for American Art.jpg|''White Phlox'', 1906.<br>[[Terra Foundation for American Art]], Chicago, Illinois\nFile:The Pestilence (formerly War).jpg|''The Pestilence (formerly War)'', c.1918.<br>[[Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts]]\nFile:The Cape Ann Shore.jpg|''The Cape Ann Shore'', 1924.<br>[[Cape Ann Museum]], Gloucester, Massachusetts\n</gallery>\n\n== Notable students ==\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[Walter Inglis Anderson]]\n*[[Sarah Baker (painter)|Sarah Baker]]\n*[[Walter Emerson Baum]]\n*[[Maude Drein Bryant]]\n*[[Arthur Beecher Carles]]<ref>{{cite book  | last = Wolanin  | first = Barbara A. | title = Arthur B. Carles: \"Painting with Color\"  | publisher = Museum Press Inc  | year = 1984  | location = Washington, D.C. | isbn = 0-943836-00-X }}</ref>\n*[[Elizabeth Kitchenman Coyne]]\n*[[Edith Emerson]]\n*[[Nancy Maybin Ferguson]]\n*[[Allan Freelon]]<ref name=\"CAPEANN\"/>\n*[[Ella Sophonisba Hergesheimer]]\n*[[Marie Hull]]\n*[[Thomas Lorraine Hunt]]\n*[[Susette Schultz Keast]]\n*[[Harriet Randall Lumis]]<ref name=\"CAPEANN\">{{cite web | url=https://www.capeannmuseum.org/collections/artists/hugh-henry-breckenridge/ | publisher=Cape Ann Museum | title=Hugh Henry Breckenridge}}</ref>\n*[[John Marin]]\n*[[Delle Miller]]<ref>{{cite web| url=https://kuscholarworks.ku.edu/bitstream/handle/1808/1028/BDKAversion1.pdf?sequence=1| title=Biographical Dictionary of Kansas Artists (active before 1945)| first=Susan V.| last=Craig| year=2006|access-date=3 May 2019| page=148}}</ref>\n*[[Mary Elizabeth Price]]<ref name=\"Peterson p. 194\">{{cite book|author1=Brian H. Peterson|author2=William H. Gerdts|title=Pennsylvania Impressionism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rd0T303qF90C&pg=PA194|date=27 September 2002|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|isbn=0-8122-3700-5|page=194}}</ref>\n*[[Leopold Seyffert]]\n*[[Mary Given Sheerer]]\n*[[Nan Sheets]]\n*[[Ben Solowey]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal | first=Arthur | last=Hoeber | title=Hugh H. Breckenridge | journal=International Studio | volume=37 | number=145 | date=March 1909}}\n*{{cite news | title=Breckenridge, Hugh Henry | newspaper=New York Times | nopp=y |page=Obituary | date=5 November 1937}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|Hugh Breckenridge}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Breckenridge, Hugh H.}}\n[[Category:1870 births]]\n[[Category:1937 deaths]]\n[[Category:Artists from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Painters from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n[[Category:American landscape painters]]\n[[Category:19th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American painter}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name           = Hugh Henry Breckenridge\n| image          = Breckenridge Selfportrait 1913.jpg\n| imagesize      =\n| caption        = Self-portrait 1913\n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1870|10|6|mf=y}}\n| birth_place    = Leesburg, Virginia\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1937|11|4|1870|10|6|mf=y}} \n| death_place   = Philadelphia, Pennsylvania\n| nationality   = American\n| education     = Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts\n| field         = [[Painting]], [[Educator]]\n| training      =\n| movement      = \n| works         = \n| patrons       =\n| awards        = \n| spouse        = \n}}\n\n'''Hugh Henry Breckenridge''' (1870-1937), was an American painter and art instructor who championed the artistic movements from impressionism to modernism. Breckenridge taught for more than forty years at the [[Pennsylvania Academy of Fine Arts]], becoming the school's Dean of Instruction in 1934. He also taught from 1920 to 1937 at his own Breckenridge School of Art in [[Gloucester, Massachusetts]]. \n  \n==Biography==\nBreckenridge was born on October 6, 1870 in Leesburg, Virginia. He attended the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts where he met first met [[William Edmondson]].<ref name=\"SullivanGoss\">{{cite web|last1=MacDonald|first1=Aubrey E.|title=Hugh Breckenridge (1870-1937)|url=http://www.sullivangoss.com/hugh_Breckenridge/|website=Sullivan Goss|accessdate=21 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822070636/http://www.sullivangoss.com/hugh_Breckenridge/|archive-date=22 August 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1892, he traveled to Paris where he studied under [[Adolphe William Bouguereau]].<ref name=\"askART\">{{cite web|title=Hugh Breckenridge  (1870 - 1937)|url=http://www.askart.com/artist/Hugh_Henry_Breckenridge/89871/Hugh_Henry_Breckenridge.aspx|website=askART|accessdate=21 April 2018}}</ref> He travel though Europe with his colleague [[Walter Elmer Schofield|Walter E. Schofield]].<ref name=\"askART\"/>\n\nIn 1894 when he returned to Philadelphia he began his career at the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts (PAFA), where he would teach for more than forty years.<ref name=\"askART\"/><ref name=\"Tran\">{{cite web|last1=Tran|first1=Hoang|title=Hugh Breckenridge papers: Finding Aid|url=https://www.pafa.org/sites/default/files/media-assets/MS.036_HughBreckenridge.pdf|website=Dorothy and Kenneth Woodcock Archives|publisher=The Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nBreckenridge opened his own school in Gloucester, Massachusetts, the Breckenridge School of Art, where he taught summer classes every year from 1920 to 1937.<ref>{{cite book | title=Paintings & Sculpture at the National Academy of Design: 1826-1925 | volume=1 | first=David B. | last=Dearinger | page=64}}</ref>\n\nBreckenridge exhibited widely from 1896 until his death, starting at the [[Art Club of Philadelphia]] and, towards the end of his life, in 1934, at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art|Whitney Museum]].<ref name=\"SullivanGoss\"/> His work was included in the 1926 [[Sesquicentennial Exposition|Philadelphia Sesqui-Centennial Exhibition]].<ref name=\"SullivanGoss\"/>\n\nBreckenridge was a member of the [[Philadelphia Art Alliance]], [[Philadelphia Sketch Club]], and the Arts Club of Philadelphia.<ref name=\"SullivanGoss\"/>\n\nHe died on November 4, 1937 in Philadelphia, while he was still on the faculty of the PAFA.<ref name=\"Tran\"/><ref name=\"SullivanGoss\"/>\n<gallery widths=\"165px\" heights=\"165px\">\nFile:Hugh Henry Breckenridge, White Phlox, 1906, oil on canvas, Terra Foundation for American Art.jpg|''White Phlox'', 1906.<br>[[Terra Foundation for American Art]], Chicago, Illinois\nFile:The Pestilence (formerly War).jpg|''The Pestilence (formerly War)'', c.1918.<br>[[Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts]]\nFile:The Cape Ann Shore.jpg|''The Cape Ann Shore'', 1924.<br>[[Cape Ann Museum]], Gloucester, Massachusetts\n</gallery>\n\n== Notable students ==\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[Walter Inglis Anderson]]\n*[[Sarah Baker (painter)|Sarah Baker]]\n*[[Walter Emerson Baum]]\n*[[Maude Drein Bryant]]\n*[[Arthur Beecher Carles]]<ref>{{cite book  | last = Wolanin  | first = Barbara A. | title = Arthur B. Carles: \"Painting with Color\"  | publisher = Museum Press Inc  | year = 1984  | location = Washington, D.C. | isbn = 0-943836-00-X }}</ref>\n*[[Elizabeth Kitchenman Coyne]]\n*[[Edith Emerson]]\n*[[Nancy Maybin Ferguson]]\n*[[Allan Freelon]]<ref name=\"CAPEANN\"/>\n*[[Ella Sophonisba Hergesheimer]]\n*[[Marie Hull]]\n*[[Thomas Lorraine Hunt]]\n*[[Susette Schultz Keast]]\n*[[Harriet Randall Lumis]]<ref name=\"CAPEANN\">{{cite web | url=https://www.capeannmuseum.org/collections/artists/hugh-henry-breckenridge/ | publisher=Cape Ann Museum | title=Hugh Henry Breckenridge}}</ref>\n*[[John Marin]]\n*[[Delle Miller]]<ref>{{cite web| url=https://kuscholarworks.ku.edu/bitstream/handle/1808/1028/BDKAversion1.pdf?sequence=1| title=Biographical Dictionary of Kansas Artists (active before 1945)| first=Susan V.| last=Craig| year=2006|access-date=3 May 2019| page=148}}</ref>\n*[[Mary Elizabeth Price]]<ref name=\"Peterson p. 194\">{{cite book|author1=Brian H. Peterson|author2=William H. Gerdts|title=Pennsylvania Impressionism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rd0T303qF90C&pg=PA194|date=27 September 2002|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|isbn=0-8122-3700-5|page=194}}</ref>\n*[[Leopold Seyffert]]\n*[[Mary Given Sheerer]]\n*[